  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most Queensland property sales proceed without one. But when a statutory declaration is required, sellers are sometimes surprised to discover they cannot simply sign a form and post it. A stat dec carries the same criminal penalties as perjury if made falsely, and it must be witnessed in a specific way. Understanding when you need one, and how to get it right, removes a potential delay from your settlement timeline.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is a statutory declaration?</h2>
      <p>A statutory declaration is a written statement of facts that the person making it swears or affirms to be true before an authorised witness. It is a formal legal document governed by the <em>Oaths Act 1867</em> (Qld). Making a false declaration is a criminal offence. Unlike a standard signature on a contract, a stat dec requires you to appear in person before a qualified witness and sign it in their presence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When Queensland property sellers may need one</h2>
      <p>Not every sale requires a statutory declaration, but several common situations trigger the requirement:</p>

      <p><strong>Pool safety compliance.</strong> If your property has a pool and you do not have a current pool safety certificate, you have two options at contract: obtain the certificate before settlement, or provide a statutory declaration confirming either that no pool exists or that you acknowledge the buyer takes on the compliance obligation. Your conveyancer will advise which approach suits your situation, but if you choose the declaration route, it must be made before settlement.</p>

      <p><strong>Smoke alarm compliance.</strong> Sellers in Queensland must declare at settlement that the property complies with the Queensland smoke alarm legislation in force at the time of sale. In practice this is often handled through a clause in the standard contract, but in some transactions a separate stat dec is required to formally confirm compliance. Your solicitor will tell you if this applies to your sale.</p>

      <p><strong>Identity verification.</strong> In some conveyancing situations, particularly where there is any ambiguity about the seller's identity or their relationship to the property, the buyer's solicitor or lender may request a statutory declaration confirming the relevant facts. This is more common in deceased estate sales and in situations where the property title was registered under a slightly different name to the seller's current identification documents.</p>

      <p><strong>Deceased estate sales.</strong> Executors and administrators selling on behalf of an estate regularly need to make statutory declarations confirming their authority to act, the circumstances of the estate, or the identity of beneficiaries. If you are selling as executor and you have not sold estate property before, expect your solicitor to advise on the declarations required.</p>

      <p><strong>Lost or unavailable documents.</strong> A statutory declaration can sometimes substitute for a lost original document, such as a title deed that cannot be located. Whether this is acceptable depends on the specific document and the circumstances, so this is always a matter for your solicitor.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who can witness a statutory declaration in Queensland?</h2>
      <p>The witness must be one of the following:</p>
      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li>A Justice of the Peace (JP)</li>
        <li>A Commissioner for Declarations (Cdec)</li>
        <li>A solicitor or barrister</li>
        <li>A notary public</li>
        <li>Any other person listed in the schedule to the <em>Oaths Act 1867</em> (Qld)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>For most sellers, the simplest option is a JP. They are widely available at Queensland public libraries, courthouses, and some police stations. The Queensland Government maintains a JP in the Community finder at the Department of Justice website, which allows you to search by location and day. Many RAQ offices also provide JP services. Your solicitor can witness the declaration if you are seeing them in person.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The witnessing process: what to expect</h2>
      <p>Bring the unsigned declaration and valid photo identification to your appointment. The witness must see you sign the document. You cannot sign it in advance and then have someone witness your existing signature. The sequence is: appear before the witness, confirm your identity, read and acknowledge the content of the declaration, then sign in the witness's presence. The witness then signs and adds their qualification details.</p>

      <p>The appointment is usually brief. A JP at a library will typically take five to ten minutes. There is no charge for JP services in Queensland.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The one mistake that voids a declaration before you start</h2>
      <p>Do not sign the declaration before appearing before the witness. This is the most common error sellers make. If you sign the form at home and then take it to a JP to witness, the declaration is invalid. It cannot be corrected by the witness countersigning it later. You would need to obtain a fresh form and repeat the process. In a tight settlement timeline, that delay is easily avoided by understanding the requirement upfront: the witness must observe the signing, not certify a document that is already signed.</p>

      <p>Making a false statutory declaration is a criminal offence under Queensland law. The declaration must accurately reflect the facts as you genuinely understand them. If you are unsure whether you can make a particular declaration truthfully, speak to your solicitor before signing anything.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do next</h2>
      <p>If your solicitor has told you that a statutory declaration is required for your sale, ask them to provide the form and confirm exactly what it needs to state. Do not draft one yourself. Then locate a JP near you using the Queensland Government finder, book an appointment if required, and attend with your photo ID and the unsigned form. Allow yourself a few days of buffer before the declaration is needed for settlement, so that any issues with the document can be addressed without pressure.</p>

      <p>Your conveyancer manages this process regularly. If you are uncertain about any aspect of a statutory declaration requirement in your sale, call them first rather than trying to navigate it independently.</p>

